            <info type="description">
                        <p>CHAT (Codes for the Human Analysis of Transcripts) is the most common
                                    format for transcribing, encoding and analysing child language
                                    data. It was developed by Brian MacWhinney within the CHILDES
                                    (Child Language Data Exchange System) Project. All of the
                                    transcripts in the CHILDES database are encoded in the CHAT
                                    format. </p>
                        <p>By using the CHAT format, transcribed data can be annotated with
                                    different levels of linguistic information such as phonological,
                                    morphological or syntactic information. The data transcribed and
                                    annotated in CHAT, are compatible with some analysis tools, for
                                    example CLAN provided also by the CHILDES Project. </p>
                        <p>Since the CHAT format is widely recognized in children’s language
                                    research, many transcription tools (such as ELAN, EXMARaLDA,
                                    Praat, Phon, Transcriber) supports it. These tools can also
                                    export and import data encoded in various formats as CHAT
                                    formatted data.</p>
            </info>
